@node "Preface" "Introduction"
@toc "Introduction"
@{U}1.1  Preface                                                     zView@{u}

Here comes version 1.0 of zView. Even though there are only some 
small changes to zView's user interface since Zorro's BETA7, a lot of 
things have changed behind the scenes. First of all, MiKRO has made a 
great effort that everyone with some knowledge of GEM programming can 
compile and update zView.

Now, there is a support page and source code base on SourceForge for 
Zorro's tools for Atari/GEM, including the applications zView and 
zWeather. Zorro is the original author of zView and zWeather. He did 
all and everything that a lot of stuff had not to be re-invented. He 
made use of existing libraries and modularised his code in a way it 
can be taken over for other projects. MiKRO has followed this idea. 
He has opened the SourceForge website, adapted zView's code in all 
aspects to GCC, improved some stuff and fixed bugs in zView and the 
libraries (the same goes for zWeather).

As if this would not be enough, he has updated almost all libraries
used by zView and compiled a new version. Thanks to all his efforts,
zView is now a little bit faster and more stable. In addition, it has
a better file format support, for example, zView now supports the
latest PDF specification and can display still more TIFF variants.

At the end of the 2011, I got in contact with MiKRO because of
his BETA8 release of zView. As discovered later, changes in the code
of the plugins prevented zView from running under MagiC. He was so
kind and fixed the code even if it was not an easy task. Moreover, he
was open-minded to implement some small suggestions for zView. This
was so motivating for me that I have revised the whole documentation.
I had written the last version of the hypertext for BETA6. Now, all
features are documented. And the @{"glossary" LINK "Glossary"} is as
well up-to-date. If you want to know what @{"bit planes" LINK "Colour Depth"} are, or a
@{"palette-based" LINK "Colour Depth"} or a 32-bit @{"true-colour" LINK "Colour Depth"} image is, read the entry Colour
Depth, and in case you would like to get information about the
standard picture format of our beloved Atari GEM computer family,
then have a look at the entry GEM (X)IMG.

Come on now, catch your digital camera, take some great photos and
view them with zView on your Atari TT, your CT60/63-accelerated
Falcon, your FireBee or any other fast Atari-compatible system.

The latest news: Zorro seems to be back. He is working on his very
promising Atari desktop zDesk. And as if this is not impressing
enough, he is planning zView 2!

Germany, 3rd March 2013

Sascha Uhlig

@endnode


@node "What is zView?" "Introduction"
@toc "Introduction"
@{U}1.2  What is zView?                                              zView@{u}

zView is a plugin-based image and PDF browser, viewer and converter
for Atari TOS and compatible systems.

This software is designed for modern TOS-compatible operating systems
and is under the free software license @{"GPL" LINK "General Public License (GPL)"}.


zView's features:

  Loading of JPEG (@{"codec" LINK "Codec"} with DSP support), TIFF (almost all
   variants), GIF (with animation support), PNG, BMP, TGA, GEM (X)IMG
   (@{"true colour" LINK "Colour Depth"} as well), DEGAS (even the compressed ones),
   NEOchrome, GodPaint and Eureka RAW

  Saving in JPEG, TIFF or GodPaint format with a lot of options

  Fast thumbnail browsing

  @{"Exif specification" LINK "Exif"} support

  Powerful PDF reader

  Easily extendable by plugins

  File renaming directly in the @{"browser window" LINK "Browser Window"}

  Rock-solid on every system

@endnode


