@node "Requirements" "Introduction"
@toc "Introduction"
@{U}1.4  Requirements                                                zView@{u}

zView is a GEM application. It should run in any screen resolution
and @{"colour depth" LINK "Colour Depth"}.

Nevertheless, zView has some requirements:

 ù You need at least an Atari system with a 68020 processor and an
   FPU (coprocessor). Note that you cannot use emulators which do not
   emulate an FPU, such as STEmulator, MagiCPC, MagiCMac or MagiCOSX.

 ù zView is designed for modern TOS-compatible operating systems.
   Therefore, you need TOS 4.04, MiNT 1.15.12, MagiC 5.03, or better.

 ù It requires a modern VDI for getting information about the device-
   dependent screen format. So you need a VDI with the EdDI standard.
   NVDI (from v2.5), NOVA-VDI, the VDI of MagiC, fVDI and MVDI
   support it. If you have got no modern VDI, you can use your VDI
   with VDI-Enhancer by the Behne brothers. You can find it in the
   folder 'Goodies' of this distribution.

 ù And it needs at least 4 MB RAM. This is enough for zView and to
   load some pictures. If you want to read PDF documents, you need at
   least 16 MB of free RAM.


To run at its best:

 ù A really fast computer (such as an Atari TT, an Atari Falcon with
   a CT60/63 @{"[1]" LINK "[1]"}, a FireBee or a fast ARAnyM system),

 ù plenty of RAM (specially when using @{"true-colour" LINK "Colour Depth"} pictures and PDF
   documents),

 ù a graphics card (we are still waiting for the SuperVidel for our
   beloved Falcon CT60/63 ;-) and

 ù a multitasking system (such as MagiC, or MiNT with N.AES/XaAES/
   MyAES).

@endnode


@node "Installation" "Introduction"
@toc "Introduction"
@{U}1.5  Installation                                                zView@{u}

Please install zView as follows:

 ù Depack the archive and copy the zView folder wherever you like.

 ù For correct rendering of PDF files with TrueType fonts, you must
   create a directory for temporary files, for example C:\Tmp\.

   Enabling the operating system to find the temporary folder, you
   have to set the environment variable TMPDIR or set, at least under
   MagiC and MiNT, a symbolic link on pseudo drive U to it:

     @{B}TOS@{b}

      You can use SENF by Thomas Binder to set the environment
      variable. You can find it in the folder 'Goodies' of this
      distribution. After installing SENF according to its
      documentation, you have to add the following line to SENF.inf:

@line 7 64 0 0 7
@line 7 0 3 0 7
@line 71 0 3 0 7
       ...
       TMPDIR=C:\TMP
       ...
@line 7 64 0 0 7

     @{B}MagiC@{b}

      Under MagiC, you do not need a program like SENF to set the
      environment variable. Just put the following line to your
      MagX.inf:

@line 7 64 0 0 7
@line 7 0 3 0 7
@line 71 0 3 0 7
       ...
       #_ENV TMP=C:\Tmp\
       ...
@line 7 64 0 0 7

      If you do not like making changes to a configuration file via
      an editor, you can make use of MagiC-Configurator by Philipp
      Donz‚ supplied with MagiC.

      In case you would like to set a symbolic link instead of an
      environment variable, install Link 2 U by Daniel Augsburger.
      Along with the manual, it can be found in the folder 'Goodies'
      of this distribution. You need the following line in Link2U.cnf:

@line 7 64 0 0 7
@line 7 0 3 0 7
@line 71 0 3 0 7
       ...
       sln C:\Tmp U:\tmp
       ...
@line 7 64 0 0 7

     @{B}MiNT@{b}

      Under MiNT, you can use the setenv command for environment
      variables and sln for symblic links; therefore, put one of the
      following lines to your MiNT.cnf:

@line 7 64 0 0 7
@line 7 0 3 0 7
@line 71 0 3 0 7
       ...
       setenv TMPDIR c:/tmp
       ...
@line 7 64 0 0 7

@line 7 64 0 0 7
@line 7 0 3 0 7
@line 71 0 3 0 7
       ...
       sln c:/tmp u:/tmp
       ...
@line 7 64 0 0 7

      Please note that MiNT.cnf has to be saved with Unix line
      endings. Best is to edit in qed since it automatically saves
      them for text files with such line endings.

   Of course, if your temporary folder has another name and/or is not
   in the root directory of drive C, you have to change the path to
   your temporary folder in the lines above. And in case of a case-
   sensitive file system (common for Unix-compatible file systems
   under MiNT), you must pay attention to upper- and lowercase
   letters in folder names.

 ù And if you have got no modern VDI (see Requirements), you must
   install VDI-Enhancer by the Behne brothers. It is in the folder
   'Goodies' of this distribution. Copy Enhancer.prg into your Auto
   folder. When you use SpeedoGDOS, Enhancer must be loaded after it
   @{"[2]" LINK "[2]"}.


Additional possibilities:

 ù If you do not have a CPU higher than 68030 but a DSP, you can use
   Brainstorm's JPEG DSP decoder for decoding @{"JPEGs" LINK "JPEG"}. For that, you
   have to copy JPEGD.prg, which can be found in the folder 'Goodies'
   of this distribution, into your Auto folder.

 ù If you use ARAnyM, JPEG pictures can be decoded natively with the
   host CPU by Patrice Mandin's NatFeat JPEG decoder. You just have
   to copy NFJPEG.prg, as well in the folder 'Goodies' of this
   distribution, into your Auto folder (before MiNT if present @{"[2]" LINK "[2]"}).

 ù If you want to access the help file after pressing <Help>, you
   have to copy zView.hyp into your Guides folder (providing ST-Guide
   or a compatible help system is installed).

 ù If you want that zView displays a @{"zView-compatible file" LINK "Supported File Formats"} by double-
   clicking on the corresponding icon of your desktop, you have to
   install zView in your desktop for the corresponding file
   extensions. For further details, see the manual of your desktop.

 ù Some applications use zView's @{"codecs" LINK "Codec"} (for example, zWeather, also
   by Zorro). So, if you want to make the @{"codecs" LINK "Codec"} available to those
   applications, you need to install them in a global folder.

   So do the following:

   Put the folder '@{"Codecs" LINK "Codec"}' in your global LDG directory. If you do
   not use the @{"LDG system" LINK "LDG System"}, put it in C:\GEMSys\LDG\ (default LDG
   path).

@endnode


