@node "Browser Window" "Using zView"
@toc "Using zView"
@{U}2.1  Browser Window                                              zView@{u}

The browser window is the heart of zView. With it, you can browse
through drive directories to show their contents. In case of @{"zView-" LINK "Supported File Formats"}
@{"compatible pictures" LINK "Supported File Formats"}, these are displayed in a handy previewable
thumbnail format. If it is a @{"zView-compatible animation file" LINK "Supported File Formats"}, the
first frame of the animation is displayed.

If you choose the browser option in the @{"File menu" LINK "The 'File' Menu"}, a window divided
in three sections appears on the screen.


@limage "images/browser.bmp" 0


On the left is the graphical representation of the drive directories,
the so-called @{"directory list" LINK "Directory List"}. On the right are the contents of a
selected subdirectory, called @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}. The @{"toolbar" LINK "Browser Window Toolbar"} is located
above both lists.

Between the @{"directory list" LINK "Directory List"} and the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"} is a split bar. You
can move the split bar by dragging it with the mouse in order to
reduce/enlarge the space that the lists take up within the browser
window.

@endnode


@node "Directory List" "Using zView"
@toc "Using zView"
@{U}2.2  Directory List                                              zView@{u}

The directory list is on the left of the @{"browser window" LINK "Browser Window"}. It is an
extendable tree directory. It enables you to browse through drive
directories. This technique is common to many Windows and Mac
applications.


@limage "images/dirlist.bmp" 0


When a drive or folder contains folders, a right-facing triangle is
shown in front of the drive or folder icon. Clicking on it opens the
directory structure of that drive or folder below the drive or folder
name and changes the triangle to a downward-pointing triangle. A
click on the latter closes the drive or folder and hides its folders
again. But if you click on an icon of a drive or a folder, or on the
name of it, then the name of it is displayed in inverse video and the
content of the selected directory is shown in the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"} on
the right. With the first possibility, clicking on a right-facing
triangle, you can open the target folder directly, without having to
open and tediously redraw all the thumbnails in the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}
beforehand.

@endnode


@node "Contents List" "Using zView"
@toc "Using zView"
@{U}2.3  Contents List                                               zView@{u}

 2.3.1  Navigation and Selection
 2.3.2  Icon/Thumbnail Display Configuration

@line 1 70 0 0 7

The contents list on the right of the @{"browser window" LINK "Browser Window"} shows the
contents of a drive or folder selected in the @{"directory list" LINK "Directory List"}.


@limage "images/contents.bmp" 0


In the contents list, a selected directory is shown in form of icons
for folders and files with their corresponding names below the icons.
As long as 'Show file size' option in the preferences is active (see
Preferences Dialogue, subchapter Index Card 'Browser'), the size of a
file is shown below the filename, too. There are icons for folders,
programs, @{"zView-compatible picture/animation files" LINK "Supported File Formats"}, PDF files and a
standard file icon for the remaining files:


@limage "images/icons.bmp" 0


Immediately after decoding the picture or animation files, these will
be displayed in a handy previewable thumbnail format instead of a
simple picture icon.

@endnode


@node "Navigation and Selection" "Using zView"
@toc "Contents List"
@{U}2.3.1  Navigation and Selection                                  zView@{u}

In the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}, icons and thumbnails can be selected by a
single mouse-click. A frame around an icon or a thumbnail shows the
selection. You can select more than one icon or thumbnail while
pressing <Shift>, but at the moment that can only be used if you want
to delete several files and/or folders.

If a file or folder has been selected, you can

 ù click on the file or folder name in order to change it (you can do
   this directly, no dialogue is needed!),

 ù delete the file or folder with the menu entry Edit/Delete or with
   the @{"delete file(s) button" LINK "Browser Window Toolbar" "delete file(s) button"} in the toolbar,

 ù obtain some information about the file or folder (for details, see
   Information Dialogue), and,

 ù if it is a thumbnail, save the picture in JPEG, TIFF or GodPaint
   format (see Saving and Converting Pictures).


Double-clicking on a folder icon will open the subdirectory of that
folder in the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}. And a double-click on a thumbnail will
load and display the picture in its full size in a separate @{"picture" LINK "Picture Window"}
@{"window" LINK "Picture Window"}; in case of an animation file, it will show the animation in
this window; and if it is a PDF file, the PDF will be opened in the
@{"PDF window" LINK "PDF Window"}. If you want to see the directory above the present one in
the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}, you have to press the @{"go back directory button" LINK "Browser Window Toolbar" "go back directory button"} in
the toolbar.

In addition, you can navigate through the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"} with the
keyboard:

 ù The cursor keys move the selection frame.

 ù If a folder is selected, <Return> will show its subdirectory in
   the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}.

 ù If a thumbnail is chosen, <Return> will open the @{"picture window" LINK "Picture Window"}.

 ù If a PDF file is highlighted, <Return> will open the @{"PDF window" LINK "PDF Window"}.

 ù To go back to the directory above the present one, you have to
   press <ClrHome>.

@endnode


@node "Icon/Thumbnail Display Configuration" "Using zView"
@toc "Contents List"
@{U}2.3.2  Icon/Thumbnail Display Configuration                      zView@{u}

There are some options to alter the icon/thumbnail display in the
@{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}:

 ù You can alter the space that icons and thumbnails take up in the
   @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}. By pressing the buttons with a magnifying glass in
   the @{"browser window toolbar" LINK "Browser Window Toolbar"}, you can display more or fewer icons
   and thumbnails. With the left button, you can increase the space
   and fewer icons and thumbnails can be shown per row and column in
   the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}, but the thumbnails are larger. And, with the
   right one, you can reduce the space, more icons are shown and the
   thumbnails are smaller.

 ù The thumbnails display can be improved in @{"high-colour" LINK "Colour Depth"} and @{"true-" LINK "Colour Depth"}
   @{"colour" LINK "Colour Depth"} display modes (16, 24 and 32 bits). In this case, you can
   use one of many computation methods to smooth thumbnails. You can
   select them in the @{"index card 'Browser'" LINK "Index Card 'Browser'"} of the @{"preferences" LINK "Preferences Dialogue"}
   @{"dialogue" LINK "Preferences Dialogue"}. But please note that the computation methods are very
   slow, so that you had better choose them only if you have a really
   fast computer.

 ù You can change the width/height ratio of the area that icons or
   thumbnails take up in the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"} to 4:3 or to 3:4 by
   selecting the menu entry View/4:3 Thumbnails or @{"View/3:4" LINK "View/3:4 Thumbnails"}
   @{"Thumbnails" LINK "View/3:4 Thumbnails"}. If such an entry has been selected, the thumbnails are
   scaled in such a way that they can be completely displayed in the
   area with the new aspect ratio.

   Select a width/height ratio of 4:3 if you look mainly at
   horizontal pictures and a ratio of 3:4 in case you use mainly
   vertical images.

 ù If you want that, besides folders, only @{"zView-compatible files" LINK "Supported File Formats"}
   appear in the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}, deactivate 'Show unsupported files'
   in the @{"index card 'Browser'" LINK "Index Card 'Browser'"} of the @{"preferences dialogue" LINK "Preferences Dialogue"}.

 ù In case only @{"zView-compatible picture/animation files" LINK "Supported File Formats"} should be
   listed, that is to say, only thumbnails, set the check mark (tick)
   in front of the menu entry View/Show Only Images.

 ù Files and folders with the attribute hidden @{"[3]" LINK "[3]"} can be set with
   the file information box of your desktop (for example, with jinnee
   or Thing). If you want to show them in the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"}, activate
   'Show hidden files' in the @{"index card 'Browser'" LINK "Index Card 'Browser'"} of the @{"preferences" LINK "Preferences Dialogue"}
   @{"dialogue" LINK "Preferences Dialogue"}.

 ù The files in the @{"contents list" LINK "Contents List"} can be shown sorted in various ways
   that can be selected in the @{"View menu" LINK "The 'View' Menu"}. The options are: @{"View/Sort" LINK "View/Sort by Name"}
   @{"by Name" LINK "View/Sort by Name"}, View/Sort by Size and View/Sort by Date. Please note
   that, in any case, folders will appear sorted by name.

@endnode


