@node "FAQ (Frequently Asked Questions)" "Appendix"
@toc "Table of Contents"
@{U}B  FAQ (Frequently Asked Questions)                              zView@{u}

This list of more or less frequently asked questions has been divided
into sections so that you can find answers to your questions more
easily.


Questions Related to the Installation of zView
@line 1 60 0 0 7

  zView does not work.

   This application is for high-end TOS computers. An Atari Falcon
   with an FPU or an Atari TT is the MINIMUM to use this software.
   Are you sure that your computer system follows the hardware and
   software requirements (see chapter Requirements)?


  Even though zView fulfils the hardware and software requirements,
   it does not work.

   Maybe your zView archive is corrupted. Please download it again.


  When I try to open the @{"browser window" LINK "Browser Window"}, zView complains with the
   alert 'zView can't load the icons' and exits.

   In your zView directory, there must be the folder 'Icons' with the
   icons in GodPaint format (icons for the @{"directory" LINK "Directory List"} and @{"contents" LINK "Contents List"}
   list of the @{"browser window" LINK "Browser Window"}, as well as the icons for the toolbars
   of the @{"browser" LINK "Browser Window"}, @{"picture" LINK "Picture Window"} and @{"PDF window" LINK "PDF Window"}; all small icons are
   combined to one file). For some reason, this folder is missing, or
   there is something wrong with the icon files. Another reason could
   be that the GodPaint plugin is missing in the folder '@{"Codecs" LINK "Codec"}' or
   doesn't work.


  Do I have to install the whole @{"LDG system" LINK "LDG System"}?

   No, this is not neccessary. Actually, the installation of the LDG
   system is almost useless for zView's LDG @{"codecs" LINK "Codec"} because they are
   not shareable at the moment. Shareable means that, for example,
   two programs use a @{"codec" LINK "Codec"}, but only one copy is in memory. Of
   course, other applications, such as zWeather, can use these @{"codecs" LINK "Codec"}
   if installed in a global folder (see chapter Installation), they
   are just not shareable. Later versions might support this feature.


  Why are JPEG images not decoded with the installed JPEG DSP
   decoder by Brainstorm if one has a Falcon with a CPU higher than
   68030?

   It was a great decision by Atari to support the Falcon's 68030
   with a DSP. The Atari Falcon was the only home computer with such
   a chip. Nevertheless, a CPU higher than 68030 is faster for
   decoding @{"JPEGs" LINK "JPEG"} than the DSP.


Questions Related to Images
@line 1 60 0 0 7

  zView crashes with some images. What can I do?

   Go to z-tools.sourceforge.net and write a bug report for zView.


  Some images are not shown with a thumbnail (and cannot be viewed
   in its full size).

   Although zView recognises an image by the file header instead of
   the filename's extension (so that it is really the format which is
   supported by zView), there are some pictures that cannot be
   displayed. Sometimes, it is almost impossible to support all
   variants and features of an image format. For example, TIFF is
   very complex. Another reason for not displaying a picture: it
   contains incorrect or incomplete image data.


  The colours of my 16-colour @{"GEM IMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"} picture are displayed
   inaccurately.

   Your picture lacks included colour information. The original
   @{"GEM IMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"} file format has a serious defect as a colour format since
   its specification made no allowance for colour @{"palettes" LINK "Colour Depth"}. If you do
   not use the same @{"colour palette" LINK "Colour Depth"} as while saving the image, the
   picture colours are wrong. There were several attempts to correct
   the omission of @{"palette" LINK "Colour Depth"} information, but the de facto standard is
   @{"XIMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"}, for eXtended @{"IMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"} format, defined in 1990. It stores the
   @{"colour palette" LINK "Colour Depth"} in the file header and is supported by zView as
   well as almost all not too old software that deals with @{"GEM IMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"}
   images.


  I have a @{"true-colour" LINK "Colour Depth"} @{"GEM IMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"} image and it can be displayed, but
   its image content is distorted.

   It seems that your image is in PixArt TC @{"XIMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"} format. zView can
   only display GEM-View TC @{"XIMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"} pictures correctly. Unfortunately,
   there is no way of distinguishing between PixArt TC @{"XIMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"} and GEM-
   View TC @{"XIMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"} images.


  The Atari graphics application True Paint by HiSoft can save true-
   colour @{"IMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"} files; however, zView cannot read them.

   True Paint is the one of the rare examples that saves @{"true-colour" LINK "Colour Depth"}
   @{"IMG" LINK "GEM (X)IMG"} files in 16-bit instead of 24-bit @{"colour depth" LINK "Colour Depth"}, at least on
   the Falcon. Like zView, most other programs cannot read them.


  Altough zView supports JPEG-compressed TIFF pictures, they are not
   displayed.

   Your images probably use a very old JPEG-in-TIFF encapsulation.
   There were serious problems with TIFF 6.0's design for embedding
   JPEG-compressed data in TIFF (Section 22 of the TIFF 6.0
   specification of 3 June 1992). Therefore a different scheme
   described in TIFF Technical Note #2 was defined in 1995. The old
   JPEG encapsulation is now totally obsolete and deprecated for new
   applications and images.


Questions Related to PDF Files
@line 1 60 0 0 7

  Can zView display all kinds of PDF files?

   First of all, zView can display @{"PDFs" LINK "PDF"} up to the latest PDF
   specification 1.7. Like many other readers, though, zView cannot
   deal with video, sound, completable form fields, JavaScript and so
   on. You can open such a PDF, but the embedded video, for example,
   cannot be played.

  When I browse a PDF file, zView does not remember the last set
   zoom level for a page. Can this be changed?

   If the option 'Fit PDF to the window' in the @{"index card 'PDF'" LINK "Index Card 'PDF'"} of
   the @{"preferences dialogue" LINK "Preferences Dialogue"} is enabled, zView always fits the size of
   a new page to your window. You have to disbale this option.


Questions Related to the Development of zView
@line 1 60 0 0 7

  I would like to make some suggestions for zView.

   Zorro and MiKRO have made a great effort that everyone with some
   knowledge of GEM programming can compile and update zView. If you
   are no coder at all, you can go to z-tools.sourceforge.net and
   write feature requests for zView. There might be a programmer who
   like implementing your ideas. Or you can e-mail Zorro or MiKRO
   (see chapter Contact).


@endnode


