@pnode "[1]"
There are some CT60 with a 68060 without an FPU.
So, if you use your CT60 with a
- MC68LC060 (LC = no FPU),
- MC68EC060 (EC = no FPU and no PMMU), or
- MC68060 with 75 MHz (no LC letters, but it is one),
you cannot use zView!
@endnode


@pnode "[2]"
There are some tools for sorting a directory. For example,
DirectorySort by Philipp Donz‚ for FAT and VFAT file systems
is to be recommended.
You do not need a tool for sorting a directory, though:
 - Create a new folder, for example, 'Tmp'.
 - Move the Auto folder files into the new folder.
 - Copy all programs back into the Auto folder that should
   be started before program X.
 - Copy program X back into the Auto folder.
 - Copy all programs back into the Auto folder that should
   be started after program X.
 - Delete the Tmp folder.
@endnode


@pnode "[3]"
Hidden folders are not possible with all file
systems, for example, FAT or VFAT.
@endnode


@pnode "[4]"
In addition, zView supports some rare
compression algorithms:
- NeXT RLE 2-bit
- ThunderScan RLE 4-bit
- Pixar companded 11-bit Zip
- PKZIP-style Deflate (experimental)
- SGI Log Luminance RLE 32-bit (experimental)
- SGI Log Luminance RLE 24-bit (experimental)
@endnode


@pnode "[5]"
Design rule for Camera File system (DCF) is a
JEITA specification which defines a file
system for digital cameras, including the
directory structure, file naming method,
character set, file format and metadata
format. It is currently the de facto industry
standard for digital still cameras. The file
format of DCF conforms to the Exif
specification, but the DCF specification also
allows use of any other file formats.
@endnode


